		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bard holding aggro?  Charm/Snare?<a name="23581"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 24 04 3:13 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Some good questions, and I will tell you my thoughts.  It would be hard to say that there are difinitive answers for some though.
<br />

<br />
If you are using Chants (your best outright damage) the key is to kite em for a bit before others engage.  Depending on the mobs etc. you may have to guage what percent HP they should dive in at.
<br />

<br />
Snare DOES produce a lot of aggro.  If you have no healer at all, you can &quot;Aggro Drag&quot; for a group.  Again, start with standard 4-Chant kiting.  Then, after 5-10% HP, then start twisting Snare, Poison, Disease, Snare, Frost, Flame, repeat... and drag the mob back and forth.  The melees can engage (and NOT taunt) and smack the mobs from behind.  Mages must use non-rooting pets.  (They have a Rogue pet which works great).  If someone gets aggro, they back off, and for the moment, they become the Aggro-Dragger.  Usually, within a couple of ticks, you have it back.  I have done this in lots of places, including PoNightmare.
<br />

<br />
As for Snare having MORE aggro than a Chant, again, I can't confirm that without doubt.  My guess is that it does.  In the Aggro Drag scenario above, I rarely lose aggro unless someone is dumb, like a prematurely nuking Wizard or something.
<br />

<br />
As for getting aggro BACK after someone screws up and takes aggro.  (Imo, EVERY competent player in EQ is responsible for their own aggro management.  In this situation, they need to engage their brains and adjust, duh).  Getting aggro back CAN be tough, especially healing aggro.  (If you are aggro-dragging, no one should be getting hit, either)
<br />

<br />
Charm does work very well.  I cannot confirm the bit about 27 Charm having the same aggro, even when the mob is above the lvl cap of the song.  All you can do is try it.  Perhaps have a Tank class experiment with you.  Start a kite, and have them TRY to steal aggro.  When they get it, fire off the 27 Charm, and see if you get it back.  Or, let them start tanking and YOU try to steal it from them.  (Sometimes, even when someone does get small aggro, just the next chant landing gets it back.  So the latter might be a better test).
<br />

<br />
If someone gets low HP aggro, you should charm to save their life, and someone should heal them.  In my experience, when charm breaks, even your charm is not enough to keep the mob off them.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Scherzo Glissando <BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
