				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bard holding aggro?  Charm/Snare?<a name="23681"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 24 04 10:36 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Lot of good info here.  I didn't know that even procs for bards are coded differently, that's just ridiculous.  SOE really doesn't want us to have aggro.
<br />

<br />
I've played with SoS and got less than desirable results, especially at 65.  I would have loved to get an upgrade to this song, found it was really fun to use in the mid 50's.
<br />

<br />
Also played with Kazumi's and have found that it's generally not worth the confusion for a group, even one that is expecting it.  As far as I'm concerned it's definately fun to play with, but not something I would use on a regular basis.
<br />

<br />
Also definately agree that bards can hold aggro very well in a kiting group, simply by being the closest one in (potential) striking distance.  If there's enough room it's fun to run circles around your group and come in range for quick pulses of Muse/Manasong.  This is still only useful in zones with spread out kiting camps like PoD/PoV/HoH.
<br />

<br />
So basicly, what I am reading is that aggro for bards is basicly determined by one thing only: how much damage they have done to said MOB.  There's not really any tricks to get around this because of the way our songs and effects are coded.  Load up on the highest damage/proc weapons you can find and try to swap in TDoK for chants whenever possible, if doing a chant/caster twist.  Yell at casters to delay casting if they keep getting aggro, cause it ain't getting any better than that.
<br />

<br />
I still think 27 charm may have some potential and I'm going to keep playing with it, I have definately found that it will taunt aggro back to me on occasion.
<br />

<br />
Realobs</span></td>
